Crimea and Sudetenland, same fight?
BRUSSELS – Russia's takeover of Crimea constitutes the most serious example of peacetime aggression Europe has experienced since Germany's Nazi annexation of the Sudetenland in 1938.
It is certainly today common to downplay the importance of the "Munich Lessons" when referring to this episode in which Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier conceded to Hitler's demands regarding Czechoslovakia in an attempt to appease the Führer.
However, if the Western world were to turn a blind eye to the annexation of Crimea—Russia's second case of invading a sovereign territory by President Vladimir Putin, following the occupation of the Georgian regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia in 2008—current democratic leaders might deeply regret their inaction.
Within Western capitals, reactions have so far been mixed.
The sanctions currently being considered—such as expulsion from the G8, for example—might seem laughable if the threat to peace in Europe were not so serious.
Poutine considers the collapse of the Soviet Union as the most serious catastrophe of modern times, with mankind striving relentlessly to revive a fallen Russian empire.
If the West is to be taken seriously, it will have to act with the same determination that Putin shows.
The many successes of the Russian president within the framework of his imperialist project have so far cost him almost nothing.
His initiative in favor of a Eurasian Economic Community has enabled Russia to bring together a number of resource-rich states, such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan.
Georgia was dismembered in 2008.
As for the Armenian government, Russian intimidation has pushed it to reject the association agreement proposed by the European Union.
And here we have the most precious geostrategic trophy of all—the Ukraine—likely falling into Putin's hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia "ceases to be an empire," as explained by the former U.S. National Security Advisor Zbigniew Brzezinski; "on the other hand, with a Ukraine that is first bribed and then subordinated, Russia automatically becomes an empire again." And since the vast majority of Ukrainians have no desire whatsoever to join Putin's empire, it is highly likely that the country ruled by the Russian president will now become a highly militarized state, a sort of Soviet Union stripped of its Communist Party.
It is essential that the international community's response measures up to the level of recklessness demonstrated by Putin.
Canceling summits, proposing trade agreements, and participating in forums as unproductive as the G8 are not enough.
Only measures involving the imposition of tangible economic sanctions that could affect Russian citizens—who, let us remember, keep reelecting Putin to power—will allow us to hope to see the Kremlin abandon its expansionist course.
What kind of sanctions could they be?
First, Turkey could decide to close the Bosporus Strait to Russian transports, as it did after the 2008 Russia-Georgia war.
At the time, Turkey had blocked access to the Black Sea in order to prevent the United States from intervening, although it now clearly appears that this was not the intention of the United States.
Today, Turkey could choose to close the Turkish Straits not only to Russian warships, but also to all commercial vessels heading to Russian ports in the Black Sea.
The impact on Russia's economy – as well as on Putin's military claims – would prove to be significant.
Turkey is authorized to close the Dardanelles under an amendment made in 1982 to the 1936 Montreux Convention.
Thus, Turkey could turn against Putin the very motive he invoked to justify the annexation of Crimea — namely, that he was preserving the Russian ethnic groups living there — by asserting that it itself is protecting its Turkish cousins of Tatar origin, who, given the mistreatment they have suffered at the hands of Russia, clearly wish to remain under Ukrainian rule.
This week, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoğlu ordered his plane to turn back in mid-air in order to head to Kiev to provide support to the new interim government.
Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, who, as Putin knows, is not a softie either, could follow suit by immediately closing the Turkish straits to Russian transports—until Putin recalls all his troops from Crimea so they can return to their bases, namely those in Sevastopol or Russia.
It would be good if Turkey could rely on the guarantee provided by Article 5 of the NATO treaty in the event that Russia sought to intimidate it.
Secondly, the American president Barack Obama could impose on Russia the same type of financial sanctions that he imposed on Iran regarding its nuclear program.
These sanctions have indeed significantly crippled the Iranian economy.
In the same way, refusing access to the American financial system for all banks dealing with Russian banks or companies would create an unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
Russian citizens must understand that allowing Putin – whose rise to power was based on his promise to end the shortages of the early post-Soviet era – to continue his aggressive imperialist course could cost them dearly.
Thirdly, it would be possible for Obama to remind the Chinese of their role in Eurasian stability.
A true tragedy in Putin's eyes, the disintegration of the Soviet Union represented for China the most extraordinary geostrategic opportunity one could imagine.
In an instant, this empire that had seized several million hectares of Chinese territory over the centuries, and had threatened the People's Republic with nuclear annihilation, simply vanished altogether.
Since then, the independent states of Central Asia, and Ukraine itself, have become important trading partners of China.
Russia's invasion of Georgia seriously upset China, as was evident during the Shanghai Cooperation Organization summit held following the war (this regional grouping comprising several former Soviet states that share borders with China and its motherland).
Russia attempted to persuade the OSCE to recognize the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
The Organization has, however, expressed its disagreement.
Or, the Central Asian member countries — Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan — would never have been able to oppose the Kremlin without China's support.
It now belongs to Chinese President Xi Jinping, however, to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's audacity.
Indeed, the true test of this Chinese claim to be a genuine and responsible protagonist within the international community will soon take place at the United Nations.
Will China support this manifest violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it back the territorial integrity of Ukraine?
Two other sanction options are also under consideration.
Each Russian leader could thus see their visas denied or canceled.
It would also be possible to freeze a number of assets, particularly those that have been laundered by oligarchs close to Putin.
It is only when the pain becomes unbearable, particularly for the elites, that this kind of struggle that Putin is currently waging may fail.
The cost of inaction could well prove to be considerable.
Many countries, from Japan to Israel, rely on America's promise to act firmly against any serious threat to peace.
Moreover, when Ukraine gave up its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so on the express condition that the United States (alongside the United Kingdom, France, and Russia) guarantee its territorial integrity.
If Crimea were to remain annexed, no one could blame Ukraine if it decided to renuclearize its defense (something it remains technologically capable of doing).
When Chamberlain returned from Munich, Winston Churchill addressed him with the famous phrase, "You had the choice between war and dishonor."
"You have chosen dishonor, and you will have war." Obama and other Western leaders are now facing a similar choice.
If they were to choose dishonor, we can be certain that the bold Putin will eventually serve them a new war, sooner or later.
